        <p><m>{\textbf{Worksheet Exercises}}</m>:</p>
        <p>1. Recall the following theorem from lectures:</p>
        <p><m>{\mathbf{Theorem}}</m>:</p>
        <p>If <m>T_A : \mathbb{R}^n \mapsto \mathbb{R}^n</m>, and <m>S</m> is some parallelogram in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then</p>
        <me>\operatorname{volume}(T_A(S)) = |\textup{det} (A)| \cdot \operatorname{volume}(S)</me>
        <p>where <m>T_A(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m>.</p>
        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
        <p><m>S</m> is the parallelogram determined by <m>\vec{p_1} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}</m>, and <m>\vec{p_2} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}</m>.</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>What is the area of <m>S</m>?</p></li>
        <li><p>If <m>A = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</m>, what is the area of the image of <m>R</m> under the map <m>\vec{x} \mapsto A\vec{x}</m>?</p></li>
        <li><p>In one diagram, sketch <m>R</m> and its image under the transform.</p></li>
      </ol>
      </page>
      <page>
        <p>2. From the previous question: if <m>T_A : \mathbb{R}^n \mapsto \mathbb{R}^n</m>, and <m>S</m> is some parallelogram in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, that</p>
        <me>\operatorname{volume}(T_A(S)) = |\textup{det} (A)| \cdot \operatorname{volume}(S)</me>
        <p>This means that |det<m>A</m>| tells us <m>\textbf{something}</m> about how areas change under a linear transform.</p>
        <p>(a) What does |det<m>A</m>| tell us about <m>\textbf{how}</m> areas change under the transform <m>T_A(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m>?</p>
        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
        <p>(b) What does the sign of det<m>A</m> tell us about <m>\textbf{how}</m> areas change under the transform <m>T_A(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m>? Hint: think about the standard matrices for reflections.</p>
        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
    </page>
